04496nam a22005775i 9780773590090DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735900907 a10.1515/97807735900902doi  a(DE-B1597)654991  a(OCoLC)870652682  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aK695b.K78 2013 7aLAW0380202bisacsh04a346.01/732231 aKruk, Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Equal Parent Presumption :bSocial Justice in the Legal Determination of Parenting after Divorce /cEdward Kruk. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tEqual Parenting: Rights and Responsibilities -- tParenting after Divorce: Federal and International Law -- tNew Developments in National and International Socio-legal Policy -- tThe Discretionary Best-Interests Standard and the Primary Residence Model -- tThe Needs and Well-Being of Children of Divorce: Preservation of Parent-Child Relationships -- tHigh Conflict, Family Violence, and Parenting after Divorce -- tSixteen Arguments in Support of Equal Parenting -- tThe Equal-Parental-Responsibility Presumption: A Four-Pillar Approach to the Legal Determination of Parenting after Divorce -- tSpecific Challenges and Recommendations -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn custody battles over the children of separated parents, the prevailing standard of evaluating what is in the "best interests of the child" has been scrutinized because of the discretionary nature of what is "best" and because of the bias in favour of the child residing in one "primary residence." In response, a consensus is beginning to emerge that it is vitally important that children maintain meaningful relationships with both parents after divorce. In The Equal Parent Presumption, Edward Kruk proposes a child-focused approach based on a standard that considers the best interests of the child from the perspective of the child and a responsibility-to-needs orientation to social justice for children and families. Challenging previous research and received ideas, Kruk presents an evidence-based framework of equal parental responsibility as the most effective means of ensuring the protection of family relationships following divorce, and shielding children from ongoing parental conflict and family violence. The existing system of determining parental rights and responsibilities is harming families. The Equal Parent Presumption addresses a major barrier to the principle of gender equality in parenting after divorce, and proposes a viable alternative to sole custody in the form of a legal presumption of shared and equal parenting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of divorced parentsxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aCustody of children. 0aDivorcexLaw and legislation. 0aParent and child (Law). 0aParenting. 0aSocial justice. 7aLAW / Family Law / Divorce & Separation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359009040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773590090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773590090/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles